{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621247","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621247"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:51:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:51:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16683"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16683","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16683"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.12,0.75,0.03,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9374"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66327"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9374"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16683"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51776"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4938"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5038"},{"type":"tags","id":"5217"},{"type":"tags","id":"10475"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22187"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22189"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66327"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman requires suturing of a 3 cm laceration on her forearm. The doctor infiltrates lidocaine around the wound for local anaesthesia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of lidocaine?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks calcium channels in the nerve terminal","Inhibits acetylcholine release at nerve endings","Blocks voltage-gated sodium channels from inside the nerve cell","Enhances potassium efflux from nerve cells","Stabilises nerve cell membrane lipids"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking voltage-gated sodium channels from inside the nerve cell\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism of action of lidocaine. The drug exists in both ionised and un-ionised forms at physiological pH. The un-ionised form crosses the nerve cell membrane more easily. Once inside the cell, the ionised form binds to and blocks sodium channels, preventing the propagation of action potentials.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking calcium channels in the nerve terminal\u003C/strong\u003E may occur to a minor extent with some anaesthetics, this is not the primary mechanism of lidocaine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibiting acetylcholine release at nerve endings\u003C/strong\u003E is not how local anaesthetics work, as they block nerve conduction before this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhancing potassium efflux from nerve cells\u003C/strong\u003E is not a significant action of lidocaine, as it does not substantially affect potassium channels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Estabilising nerve cell membrane lipids\u003C/strong\u003E may occur due to lidocaine\u0027s interaction with the cell membrane, its primary action is specifically on sodium channels rather than general membrane stabilisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe ability of lidocaine to block sodium channels explains its effectiveness in preventing pain transmission and its use as an antiarrhythmic agent.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Lidocaine blocks voltage-gated sodium channels in nerve cell membranes, preventing action potential propagation.","Local anaesthetics exist in both ionised and un-ionised forms, with the un-ionised form crossing cell membranes more readily.","The ionised form of lidocaine binds to and blocks sodium channels from inside the nerve cell."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51776"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16683"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51776"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T18:52:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T11:42:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9374"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66327"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74"